text: Completely disappointing and utterly boring movie. It fails to deliver on both the generic jump scares as well as psychological horror. You can tell that the movie may have had an interesting concept as a short piece but does not stretch out to a full feature. This is the first film I have ever been to with audience members asleep, yawning, and leaving halfway through. The film sets up no distinguishable back story to the mirror which many critics praise as not spoon feeding to the audience which I get but unfortunately the plot is so thin that a little taste of what was going on would have been great. The mirror fails completely as a scary force and instead puts the characters through a series of poorly edited and sometimes confusing trip to relive the trauma of their childhood to which we already establish the outcome 5 minutes into the film. (On a side note, as a certified veterinary technician it made me laugh out loud that there was one scene in particular involving the family dog that uses parvo virus to explain the way the animal was acting despite the writers having no clue as to how the virus actually works but that is just a nitpick on a professional level) The movie ultimately goes no where and the psychological terror never amounts to any level of thrill or dread. I cannot stress enough how much this movie completely fails as a horror movies as well as a coherent film in general. I give the film makers credit for what they tried to do, but maybe taking a couple more courses in story telling and editing before we attempt another picture...

text: Alrighty, for whom it may interest.  Crimson Tiger here coming in with the Crimson Review on Oculus. Ok while many titles this year that have to do with the suspense, thriller or horror genre there hasn't been one quite as chilling as Oculus.  The reason this movie has such an interesting chill factor is because instead of a blunt enemy, it's instead a huge game of mind vs mind. The feeling of not being able to control your own mind is what makes this movie very scary.  I dunno personally my fear in a "monster" is more of a ghost simply because you can't really fight a ghost.  And like a ghost you can't really fight what your mind is telling you.  The concept is amazing to me. I give Oculus an 8/10. Yes it was a great movie to break away from this years pattern but it just seemed too blandly done.  It seemed like they wanted to use the minimum amount of resources which is sad because this could have done better. I could tell where the story was heading a little bit before the midway point. It's worth a watch but I'd recommend waiting for the DVD. (orsomeotherwayifyouknowwhatImeanwinkwink)

text: Just saw this movie today - Never has a horror movie really bothered me so much. And I don't mean it was disturbing or scary, but it was a movie that came SO CLOSE to being very interesting, but instead settles for mediocrity. If they really pushed the boundaries and delved more into a question of "Is this just main two character's latent psychosis and their mentality breaking down upon a traumatic injury or is something supernatural occurring here" this would've been a ground breaking movie. And for a while, it does this very successfully and it kept me guessing whether or not what I was watching real or not. But the concept seems like it's abandoned half way through the movie and it settles for mediocrity. For something that came so close to being successful, it bothers me a lot that they abandon this factor halfway through.    - Now for what it is, it's still a cut above the rest. It's not boring or insulting my intelligence like another movie I know -cough Conjuring cough-. But rather the story it presents is still very interesting, and frightening at times. It does not rely on cheap scares but rather sticks heavily to atmosphere. The movie is separated into two separate time lines (taking a page from True Detective's book) and knowing what happens in the flash backs, really help draw more focus into the atmosphere since there is no shock value or wondering to the story. The main two characters (both incarnations) are likeable and the child acting is decent. Despite missing its mark, Oculus really does stand a cut above most horror movies that have come out lately. Although it comes so close to levels of the Haunting and the Shining at times that it's almost cringe worthy in parts where they do actually give evidence that the mirror is haunted. Had they kept the idea of two separate flash backs going, and that the way one of them (or both) remembered things may not have been what actually happened, and whether or not the mirror was actually haunted would've made for a much more interesting story. But for what it was, it wasn't bad.

text: One is half responsible for his/her own emotions and for immersing oneself into the experience. In my opinion, this movie does its part of the job superbly and I enjoyed the movie a lot. It has a great plot, good acting performance, fast paced action, beautifully shot scenes and excellent chemistry between actors. And I'm not usually impressed with horror movies or mysteries, but this movie was really good, especially considering the budget. Actually, it's on my list of the best mystery horror movies. And I did not expect that the movie would be this good. To be honest, even if it would have extremely high budget, I would still be surprised by the quality. I think this tells a lot. The trailer doesn't do this movie any good and it just spoils it. I would not watch the trailer and just try the movie and I think you will be surprised as well.

text: From a technical and narrative stand-point, the movie is really good. The thing that piss me off, have more to do with the story itself.  Oh, so you've made an automated kill system that goes off while you don't have conscious control of yourself? Here's your Darwin award...  And what was the whole idea of that "investigation", anyway? Are video cameras gonna keep a ghost from choking you or mindforking you? Ghost uses radio waves? put the frickn mirror in a faraday cage to shield any signal. Enclose it in a salt circle - ghost stays in... maybe holly water - whatever cult/creed/mythology of supernatural this is supposed to subscribe to. When characters start acting stupid and do stupid stuff, I just give up on them. "You deserve to die! I can hardly wait until you finally kick the bucket, you asshats!"

text: Yes I think the general consensus is that the movie leaves a great deal to be desired. Colloquially, it was dog-shit like I commented before. The problem is that horror movies have to be made and they are pretty much running out of ideas. The old formulas have become tiresome and people have for the most part become desensitized to most horror movie "types" which means it is becoming increasingly difficult to genuinely "scare" people (the main point of a horror movie). So in a desperate attempt to be "different" and to "surprise", they often turn out absolute crap. This is but one such example, there are many, many others.

text: I hate it when people bag on a "horror" movie because it's not "scary." If y'all would look up the definition of "horror," you'd know that this movie is the absolute epitome of the word. There's were a few jump scares, and granted, I didn't really feel overwhelming terrified, as most "scary" parts were predictable; but the movie is completely shocking, and messed with my head beyond any other horror movie I've ever watched. I think the actors, having not been well known, were very good, and the twists were wonderfully put together. I'm still trying to understand how it all happened; especially the ending. It was a huge twist, and I find myself contemplating whether or not it WAS the mirror, or the guy REALLY WAS crazy. If y'all are looking for blood and guts; this obviously isn't the movie for you. But it's definitely psychologically pain-staking, and brain puzzling. I loved it.

text: I think one aspect of the movie was overlooked by viewers. when Karen sets the cameras in front of the mirror, her aim was to record the supernatural activity of the mirror. she explains the set up to her brother. The siblings then get into an argument. the brother convinces her with rational arguments saying that the mirror was just ordinary and it was their father who was responsible for all this. she then goes back to room to dismantle the equipment only to find out that the cameras  got misplaced. both of them watch the video recorded in the computer only to find out that the mirror distorted the video captured by the computer.                                 Then why in the world did she continue with the experiment. the whole purpose of setting up this experiment would ultimately turn futile because the mirror could even manipulate the cameras and the computers. had she had a modicum of common sense she would have discontinued with the experiment and focussed all her energy on destroying the mirror . cud anyone give an explanation as to why she went ahead wtht her plan?

text: i get the intertwining timelines converging, but, hm, that doesn't make it a great movie. the acting was pretty good, the direction was okay, and the jump scares/ick-factor scenes didn't detract *too* much from psychological horror aspect... but... yeah, it really seemed to lag at points.  the beginning was pretty standard, pretty boring. you really don't have to pay very close attention ~ go grab something to drink, you won't miss much of the story if you're good at piecing things together. if you're like me, you'll get the idea this writer *really* was into 'the house on haunted hill,' 'the shining,' and 'the haunting.' not that those are bad inspirations, but this isn't nearly as clever and sure as hell isn't as entertaining or even achieving that creepiness factor.   i will say it was a good effort and you can definitely do worse. it's not a gore-fest, full of naked women and cussing.  worth a rental, but you may not be blown away. then again, you probably won't feel cheated, either. :)

text: This film was okay. I'm not a fan of a lot of ghost/haunted/horror movies. I hated the movie Insidious, I thought Paranormal Activity was the dumbest pieces of crab I have ever seen, and I didn't care much for The Conjuring. With that said, I actually enjoyed Oculus. I didn't love it, but it was okay. It kind of reminded me of horror films I grew up with in 80s and 90s (hard to explain). Unlike some reviews have mentioned, this movie isn't confusing, and some parts are a bit predictable, but if you are up late and can't sleep, looking for something to watch on Netflix, I would recommend this movie. It's a good one time watch, and the pace of the film should keep you interested.

text: It's pretty upsetting that people in general don't understand this movie. It's peculiar how people screams and grimaces at horror movies that screams cheap, cliché and gore, but hates this type of intelligent horror movie. Oculus, in my opinion, is smart and digs deep in the realm of psychology. It does have jump scares but just a few, enough to maintain the barrier separating it from the cliché. Mostly, it exploits the tragedy of the Russel's years ago and now. And it has to be confusing because if this was real, you'd be incredibly confused as well; how else would you feel if you saw your 10 years old self walking around in present? And will you be scared shitless if you realised you're knee-deep in the mirror maze and there's no way out? Will you be terrified if you suddenly don't know where you are and what is real? Like halfway through a dream but there's no waking up? Also, the ending, you have to admit that it's a massive punch in the face (if the social media hasn't spoilt it for you yet).   I'd give the producers a big compliment for crafting such a good movie. We don't see this kind of depth in horror movies these days.

text: The only thing I didn't like about Oculus was the woman's plan to prove the mirror was evil.  I mean she went through all that trouble to try to capture the mirror's power on film and to make all those safeguards to prevent it from killing her, but the mirror was able to circumvent them so easily. It's like coming up with an amazingly well thought out chess strategy, but forgetting to plan for the fact that if your king gets in checkmate, you lose. That and I'm biased towards happy endings.
author: Alternative Ice

text: Spoiler Alert:  Having seen this movie, its pretty ridiculous how the daughter was supposedly trying to fight this mirror with intelligence and prove to the world the mirror is cursed, but she knew it can manipulate people's perception and has a limit on its range of influence before she even started the experiment. Setting up a timed execution trap but allowing the trap to be in full contact by themselves after the experiment started was a huge mistake, especially when she fully knew the mirror would "do everything it can to prevent it" right from the beginning as she said. If a mirror could really do the things it did in the movie, there's pretty much no way of proving its powers because all it does is control people. The most you would be able to record are plants dying really fast on camera but anything else would just look like some psychopathic people killing themselves. If it really does have a range of influence, get 1 person to place the mirror in an open field and another person with a sniper rifle to shoot it from afar.

text: Believe it or not, the most irritating thing about this movie is that Netflix won't allow me to rate it 0 stars. From the very beginning this movie annoyed me. The writing was poor, the acting was sub-par, but to be fair to the actors, they had horrible material to go off of. There was a cool concept here, and nothing more. The execution was so contrived all I could help but think immediately after viewing was exactly what Katee Sackhoff's character said about the eponymous mirror: "A bit ostentatious, don't you think?" The movie sucked its own dick and the only reason there was a story in the first place was because the characters were written to be too stupid to do the intelligent thing. You'll find yourself wanting to yell at the characters to stop doing stupid crap like resetting the kill-switch timer. All that said, I have one more question: Why the hell didn't they just make the kill switch non-lethal to a person and hang it up high and have the timer drop the mirror on the ground. Pretty sure gravity would shatter the friggin thing.

"Is this actually an apple I'm holding? Okay good it is, phew"  It happens with dreams sometimes too. Recently I had a nightmare and I screamed at someone to STFU, then I shot awake and a second later realized I was sitting up instead of laying down. text: 'How to prepare for paranormal activity and still screw up'. I only watched it just now, and I understand why the movie is so controversial. It doesn't matter wether the movie is about how far the paranormal could potentially push a person to lose grip on reality - I just didn't 'feel' the movie. Ultimately it doesn't matter how much a movie exploits a potentiality, if one doesn't enjoy watching it. Rest is a SPOILER, so be warned:  Would you seriously just assume you're conjuring up your fiancee and just stab him in the neck with a glass shard, without checking first - blindly assuming its an hallucination? When you're even remotely an out-of-the-box thinker you should've figured that the mirror could do things you wouldn't be able to predict. Even when they realized it could temporarily have them perform activities they weren't aware of, they still CHOSE to stick around. Its one thing to be stuck in a brilliant illusion, its another thing to simply make stupid decisions. Like many horrors, I feel their choices just didn't make sense. Many times one of the most frustrating things is that horrors contain characters that are either stupid or mentally weak. I love the occasional strong character that fights back. I thought it would happen in this movie... but it didn't. Pointless ending, making the boy end up back where he started.  However one wants to sugarcoat how brilliantly this movie is... it was just frustrating for me to watch. The frustrating part was partly in the truth of how society works. If you remember something correctly... but something that most people can't accept... they'll just 'shrink' you down and make you swallow enough pills until you're acceptable for the rest of society. 'We will only believe your story if its within our paradigm of what we're comfortable with.' So yeah, lucky boy. At the end of the movie he now knows whats in store for him. 'Screw the truth - we have pills to adjust your truth'.

I definitely recommend even though the ending was unexpected (I don’t know if in a good or bad way you’ll have to see for yourself).
